  { question: "What is the difference between miter and bevel?", answer: "A miter cut is an angled cut across the face of a board that changes the direction of the piece in the horizontal plane. A bevel cut is an angled cut through the thickness of the board, tilting the blade. Miters join pieces end-to-end around a corner, while bevels are used for edges, sloped surfaces, and compound angles." },
